An exploration in generating really hard no-guess minesweeper
puzzles. Still a (massive) work in progress

The goal of my exploration is twofold:

1. Generate boards requiring highly nontrivial logic. (A standard
   no-guess board can be solved mostly using trivial deductions. The
   puzzles in 14 Minesweeper Variants are more interesting and I use it
   as a benchmark of difficulty.)

2. Generate large boards (8x8 and above) reliably quickly

The generator program is compiled from genboard.c, and it outputs a
JSON representation of the board to stdout (progress is printed to
stderr). It does one forward pass to incrementally build up a small
sufficient set of initial clues, then a backward pass to prune away
redundant clues.

(Note: starting the position with a clueset is an innovation from 14
Minesweeper Variants. A standard game would typically start with a
blank board.)

Crucially, the generator relies on a powerful solver to determine
whether a given clueset is solvable without guesses, and more
specifically how much progress it can make. To maximise solver speed
and strength, it first applies some basic heuristics, failing which it
calls a custom-made cardinality SAT solver called CROCODILE, which is
theoretically able to definitively answer any Minesweeper position
(though it gets very slow on large instances).

The Makefile builds the genboard executable, as well as a test harness
in crocodile/test/crocodile_static to compare against MiniCARD (the
test script crocodile/test/run_all.sh expects the user to manually
insert the minicard_static executable).

same_board.sh is an experimental script that prints out different
reveal sets randomly generated from the same board.